text:
tl;dr, i understand what the ad is trying to convey. in fact, for the most part, i agree with the message. however, their poor use of terminology and other mishaps causes this to be just...a bad advertisement. the goal of any advertisement is to make more money for the brand, and this clearly flopped.

first of all, let's talk about the problems that are the "main focus" of the ad. bullying and harrassment. although it wasn't their intent, the ad definitely made it seem like these are exclusively masculine traits. quote, "toxic masculinity" at the beginning of the ad. this is just...wrong. i would argue that there are an equal amount of, if not more, female bullies in comparison to male bullies. and harrassment goes both ways, as has been shown by studies numerous times. to label these as "masculine", a.k.a., "traits that men generally have", is sexist. bullying and harrassment are wrong. but it's not being a man that makes bullying and harrassment a bad thing. this is my problem with the term "toxic masculinity". taking negative traits and gendering them. it's simply unnecessary and problematic. by no means am i denying that these traits exist, i just believe there is no natural link between them and manhood.

#feminism #sjw #toxicmasculinity #metoo #cancer #eastofcenter #itsokaytobeaman

text:
part 2

next up, generalization of men. "wait no they're not generalizing men bc the heroes of the ad are men!!" okay so, it's true that they aren't saying all men are bad men. however, the way they depict these heroes seems as if they have "broken away from the norm". as shown with all of the men lined up saying "boys will be boys", they are saying that naturally, most men are like this. they are saying that if men don't actively try to better themselves, they are "trash" like the negative examples of manhood depicted here. but in reality, naturally, most men are somewhere in between. they don't harrass women, they don't let their kids beat the shit out of each other, they don't cat call. and if they do, they aren't accepted in society. this shit isn't laughed about. these actions have never been acceptable for men, except among assholes. the opposite depicted in this ad, however shows literal male feminists. pretty far left, standing up for women and tearing down the "natural" behaviors of men. the men shown are either assholes or feminists, while most men are somewhere in between. these "in-between" men usually are better than the assholes and simply don't agree with or don't want to be feminists. but this ad says if you aren't a feminist, you're an asshole. and that's the problem. it's the old feminist arguement: "if you don't agree with me, you're in the wrong". basically, this ad could be seen as an attack on men. not a smart move when men are your target audience. looking at the likes and dislikes of the video, it's obvious that this was a mistake for the brand and company. gillette, if you really cared so much about equality, you'd just make your women's razors cost the same as your men's razors. not this shit. anyways, these are just some of my opinions and thoughts on the video. and as always, i'm open for a civil debate if you disagree with anything i said.

text:
well, firstly i would like to salute each and every women out there for the courage they gather to stand up for the wrong, knowing the fact that they can be abused more than the accused!
so, i definitely believe that #metoo is definitely breaking the silence to win the war.
when we talk about the entertainment industry, notable women like actors,singers,models etc march the movement and their voices are being heard unlike several lower statusâ€™s women, but the movement gained pace from both the categories!
so considering the dark side this industry has sometimes, definitely#metoo gave women a chance to open the zip they had on their lips for so long and spilling out the sufferings which they probably could have hesitated to do before.
not to ignore the fact, it can possibly be a tool of trap but that depends upon the particular woman who could do this,
whereas , most of the times, i believe itâ€™s really very hard for women to open their mouth infront of the whole world, iâ€™ll give a personal experience, when i face an eve tease, it leaves me devastated for a while no matter how strong i am and trust me it is very difficult to even tell my mum about it, but this movement somehow empowered women to open up!also, it isnâ€™t just about women, but this movement should be genderless! men suffer too, men should come up too! however the reality is that the ratio of women facing sexual assault is much more than men!
conclusion:
as i said itâ€™s heart wrenching to open up about the harassment we face.
it kills , trust me, it mentally kills.
therefore, a woman just canâ€™t go merry around blaming a man because she will have to face a lot of media, police and moreover the public for the statement she has made.
what i want is, a proper enquiry should be made against the case and there should be a proper investigation, no innocent should be ever made to suffer as it causes a major blow to the reputation and leaves a scar for lifetime even on a manâ€™s heart.
#metoo succeeds when now in the industry, men will think a hundred times before the assault , therefore definitely â€œ me tooâ€ is a silence breaker to win the war!just, a proper and thorough enquiry and investigation should be made.

text:
i have been practicing an attitude of gratitude for a few months now and i love it.  i like to sit down once a day 5-7 days a week and just write down 3 things that i am grateful for that day.  we all go through struggles.  in all our lives there is the good, bad, ugly, beautiful, hard, easy, ect.  even during the hard times you can find 3 things to be grateful for.  doing this daily has helped me to see all the good in my life even when it doesnâ€™t seem like life is that good.  i have retrained my mind to see the good first and to be grateful for it.  someone else always has it worse than we do. we need to be grateful for what we have. i encourage you to try this.  i bought a gratitude journal on amazon, it was super cheap for my birthday. it was the best gift i could have gifted my self.  gratitude!

today i am grateful for: 1. william and his sweet heart towards me and the dogs.  he is so sweet with us and he makes sure that he is always doing little acts of service to make us happy.  2. i am grateful for my young living team members, you guys keep me going.  i learn so much from all of you and i love to help you on your wellness journeys. 3. i am grateful for my health.  i was not well 6 years ago and i am so happy to see the difference in my body since i have started a wellness journey through diet, exercise and now using essential oils. itâ€™s been a long journey but so worth it. 
what are you grateful today? comment below, i want to hear from all of you.  letâ€™s all have an attitude of gratitude today.
.

.
.

text:
growing up whenever someone mentioned the country lebanon it conjured images of  sterotypical american propaganda of the 80â€™s/90â€™s arabian culture: curvy swords, camels, bombs, sultan looking ass dudes. but what was it actually like growing up there? especially during a civil war? my guest on derek mansplains it all is nataly aukur, a comic who was born in beirut and immigrated to america 3 years ago. on the podcast today, nataly dispels some of the myths about the stereotypes that i had always been taught. we talk about her christianity, how christianity is a minority religion (as opposed to america where it is the majority), the possibility of being sniped on her way to school and how she experienced prejudice from other disenfranchised groups. -
-
we had a great talk about how privileged americans are to be offended, her appreciation of the freedom of speech and her fear of admitting how great she has it now that she is in america. check out the latest episode of my podcast â€œthe america i am seeingâ€ on itunes, spotify and googleplay.
-
-
check out nataly on twitter and instagram: @natyourcolor
-
-

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

reuters

former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
i am in loving the information from our new product!  for some of you,  this may be a confusing 
gibberish style post; for others, i know research is your love language. #metoo

my new product has an ingredient in it called "grains of paradise" which is in the ginger family, closely related to cardamom......and wow. donâ€™t worry it is #glutenfree as the â€œgrainâ€ part is only in the name! the scientific studies on pubmed for this ingredient are incredible. basically, it helps to activate the brown fat which your body thermogenically burns for fuel and it transforms the white fat (visceral fat) to brown fat.....hence the #fatburning capabilities. white fat is generally found in your #stomach, #hip and #thigh areas. how fascinating is that?! what a game changer!

this is definitely going to be a product where inches lost is going to be an important measure, but i love diving into the why behind how things work.

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/24759256

https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/23308394

text: for the men threatened by this new wave of accountability, for the aunt and uncle who attempt to morally equivalate racists with those opposed to it, for the transphobic parent shutting out there child, for wall supporters, and so, so many others, were trying to tell you this. this is at the very core. this is not a blanket statement claiming love is all we need, thatâ€™s toxic thinking (see my post about spiritual bypassing) when you truly care for others youâ€™re willing to sit with the uncomfortable and learn about your biases, acknowledge your privileges, de-center yourself, willing to make small changes, such as using preferred gender pronouns, to educate yourself and others like you about how to turn that care and love into action. how to turn that love into dismantling systems that oppress others. love and caring cannot be passive. i made this out of frustration after conversations with my grandparents. it drains me, it breaks my heart and is overwhelming and this sentiment is the cumulative sigh i let out when i feel exasperated with them. #deepbreaths

text:
'back off' #metoo - apart from the multiple other instances i've had, this needed voice

given the literate surroundings, if you thought urban mindsets were different from the rural, it's shattering for me to break to you that it's not much different.

women are still 'objects' (some maybe of desire, some maybe just for the sheer fun of anatomy dissection) for the pleasure of others - (men & yes, devastatingly, other women too). when the causal & so-called 'harmless', 'just-checking-out' takes a new form.

maybe owing to how we are conditioned growing up as indian children, but that, will never be a justification that's good enough.

only distinction i can think of between the urban and rural men is that the course of action they adopt. a rural boy will chase the simpleton to rip her choli apart. the urban guy is supposedly informed & civil, but sadly with the same mindset.

the action of rape is a crime, but the virtual pleasure isn't, right? he would hence, not rape her through actions, but will also not think twice before visually molesting her.
doesn't this still qualify as sexually harassment too?

while we know objectification of a person - (woman or man, yes why exclude him?) is downright wrong, but making jokes about it is okay, right? the excuse that it's just in plain humour!

shaming someone for something they have absolutely no control over, calling names like small penis or big boobs or tiny melons is not funny. it is just not a subject matter to joke about. no.

it's so sad that when people run out of topics to enjoy their general banter, discussing people's bodies comes to the rescue to become the laughing stock.

ludicrous to understand that these otherwise 'so-smart minds', cannot understand the grave repercussions this can have for someone they were 'so-generally' joking about.

it's at the cost of someone's self-esteem, making them conscious of their own bodies, spiralling mental complexes, leaving them deeply underconfident in their own skin. throwing them into a never-ending trench of identity crisis, pushing them to get stuck in the vicious trap of depression which can be life-threatening. it is just not funny.

read in the comment below.

can we talk about raising boys in the #metoo climate? iâ€™ve just read a fantastic post by @tobyandroo about the #gillette advert, and the volume of people who attacked it. â£
seriously??? what is there in that ad to find offensive? â£
â£
as a woman who worked in the city, in a very male-dominated arena, i noticed very little misogyny. what bits i did get was from twits with an â€˜aâ€™ who fell victims to karma all in good time. from what iâ€™ve read though, this said more about me than it did about attitudes to women at work in general. â£
â£
iâ€™m genuinely shocked at the appalling things iâ€™m hearing, and itâ€™s made me pay more attention to what i see on a daily basis. and hereâ€™s why i think that ad needs to be just the first of many, many more like it: â£
â£
1: my 13yo daughter and her friends got wolf-whistled in the summer. and i told her it was the norm (that feels like a bit of a betrayal, i can tell you, but i want her to learn how to handle herself). they were 13. they look incredible, but thatâ€™s not the point, is it? they should be allowed to look incredible, without worrying about what men might do or say to them.â£
â£
2: i have an 11yo boy. the things i see some of that age group saying already worry me in their sexist, and misogynistic nature. i know theyâ€™re just mucking in with the rest of the boys, trying to be cool, thinking itâ€™s the thing to do. and stereotypically, i know the girls are just eyerolling, and thinking â€œhow patheticâ€¦â€ theyâ€™re handling it.â£
â£
so what should parents do? our kids arenâ€™t with us all the time, so we canâ€™t correct every bad call they make. i know that itâ€™s all just bravado and bluster, none of it is serious. but if we let it slide, will it become more? will it at best underline an ongoing attitude that supports other menâ€™s bad behaviour in the future? and how will we ever get to a point where girls donâ€™t have to learn to â€˜handleâ€™ it? â£
â£
with a foot in both camps - as the mum of both boy and girl - i have to admit that on this iâ€™m struggling. anyone else?â£
â£
if you havenâ€™t read harrietâ€™s post yet, go have a look, and tell me what you think.â£

text:
#metoo

this is an open letter to me and too all the girls out there. 
it's your body and only yours and nobody i repeat nobody has the right to touch it, tame it,  torture it,  hurt it, harm it or harrass it. not even your husband, boyfriend, partner, relatives, strangers or perverts out there.

i want to talk about an unpleasant incident that happened to me a few days ago while i was at the theatre.

the movie had just begun & i felt something touch my waist. 
initially, i thought it was nothing, but then it happened again; those filthy hands touched my sides again. i was shocked, disgusted and completely taken aback.

i grabbed that hand trying to move on my waist, turned back to look at the guy sitting in the back row, grabbed the pervert by his collar and rained down on him with a few hard slaps to put him in a world of shame and embarrassment.

while i was still trying to deal with what actually happened, & the realisation of the sudden courage that i mustered to stand up & defend myself, that guy quickly disappeared in the dark.

i could have made a racket and even taken him to the mall staff or the police. tbh, i was completely zoned out, disgusted by those perverse feelings. but somewhere deep in my heart i am proud that i could gather the courage to do what i did. and i'm pretty sure that guy'll remember the slaps he got before he even thinks of touching anyone else. 
what is most surprising about this incident is that all this while a group of guys and girls were sitting next to me and not a single person intervened or even had the courtesy to check on me.

maybe they would have if it had happened to someone they knew. 
we have seen, heard and some have even experienced sexual assaults.

these watchful perverts have taken advantage of crowded places like markets, public transports, public places to grope or brush their elbows or body parts against women.

but unless we don't make that noise, unless we don't answer back or stand up for ourselves first, this would keep happening.
so, please, i urge all you women out there, don't keep quiet!! coz nobody has a right to touch your body without your consent! 
#metoomovement

text:
one of the most difficult things a woman could do is learn to set boundaries for herself and her  children when faced with abuse in her home. it is okay to say "no" to a bully and abuse when the home is no longer safe. do not let your significant other degrade you as a woman, as person, or as a human being. 
remember that your children are watching. they look up to you and your significant others as their role models. 
the "traditional" wife had the "job" of raising the family at home. the "modern" mother must teach her son's how to respect women, to live with dignity, and to emulate a life fueled by the sentiment of self-respect. @aadagirl 
thank you @myexisapsychopath for inspiring me to share this message.

text:
what does everyone think about the new @gillette ad? âš¡ï¸shaving company gillette has been bombarded with both praise and abuse after launching an advertising campaign promoting a new kind of positive masculinity.
engaging with the #metoo movement, the companyâ€™s new advertising campaign plays on its 30-year tagline â€œthe best a man can getâ€, replacing it with â€œthe best men can beâ€.
the advertisement features news clips of reporting on the #metoo movement, as well as images showing sexism in films, in boardrooms, and of violence between boys, with a voice over saying: â€œbullying, the metoo movement against sexual harassment, toxic masculinity, is this the best a man can get?â€
the film, called we believe: the best men can be, immediately went viral with more than 4m views on youtube in 48 hours and generated both lavish praise and angry criticism. watch the full video in our bio #thebestmencanbe #gilette #thursdaythoughts #realmenarefeminists ğŸ’ª

text:
itâ€™s really hard for me, living with all these negative emotions. i used to be really confident. i didnâ€™t give a shit about what i look like or what people think of me. then, my body and my soul were abused. it got a lot harder to go out in public. i feel stared at all the time. being around men is really tough. yet, i know i like men. i like the way they see the world, cause they have different experiences. i know  that the majority of them are good people, but i canâ€™t help being scared. i donâ€™t want to be scared.
also, iâ€™m beyond pissed at my attacker for ruining my ability to interact with people. i donâ€™t believe that someone can like me for who i am anymore. if someone comes up to talk to me, itâ€™s because they wanna use me and then throw me away, no? so i distance myself from people. i donâ€™t want to distance myself.
i am (or i was? i donâ€™t know anymore) a very sexual person. i like everything related to sensuality or sexuality. i am really open to all forms of sexual/sensual expression. i like reading about it, iâ€™m happy to see people living their truth and desires. it somehow makes me feel hopeful about my future. then again, i feel trapped in. when my partner touches me, i feel guilty and gross from enjoying it.

itâ€™s an ongoing conflict with myself. i fight to go back to who i used to be. i am gonna win.

hello all! so last time i had an far-reaching topic discussion with my campus princess sisters!ğŸ’– the topic was weighty enough that made the society think about it so much with ofcourse different perspectives yet again! *-me too campaign: tool to trap or breaking silence to win the war?* so according to me, the question itself has so weight to answer the cause as we can see the upfront in the society who are victim of abuse. 
many men in the fields of art, media and films have been called out by women who accused them of sex harassment and inappropriate behaviour. but due to one woman i think now no woman is silent.
each and everyday the crimes related to women's are increasing. #metoo gives them the opportunity to share their stories because as campare to the earlier situation of women,if anything she used to face before she didn't able to speak because of the society.but now she had that chance,she can fight for herself,for her dignity and family.she is no more weaker now.
i firmly believe that all the women who are victims of sexual harassment must raise their voice. a woman must complain about such incidents, immediately at the time of its occurrence. and it is true that even a man can get trapped into this issue without reason but that doesn't mean we will stop raising the voices.
also, many allegations has put forward on this topic whether the start of the #metoo topic has arised in a true or false manner but the later cause is the perfect decision that has happened and made the society firm and strong enough to talk about their harrasement issues. also, allegations should be investigated rather than blindly trusted.
i would conclude saying that barely a week goes by now without another case of rape or historic sex abuse being splashed across the news and picked over by critics. yet misunderstanding about the nature of sexual violence leads to distorted opinions, which can further enhance victimsâ€™ feelings of shame, guilt and self-blame. so i think their should be a good justice with proper investigation should take place. thank you!

text:
it is no surprise that this is a favourite with award panels (golden globes, bafta, oscars) as this is a movie that actors and film-makers adore. the favourite is a finely crafted movie and praise to actors olivia colman, emma stone and rachel weisz whose performances are both assured and credible. align this to a screenplay both well-written and engaging along with visionary director yorgos lanthimos who has taken all of these elements and crafted a movie that, while it wonâ€™t appeal to some is, in itself a period drama that compares favourably to the work of sally potter (orlando) and peter greenaway (the draughtsmanâ€™s contract).
set in 1708, a frail and eccentric queen anne rules along with her confidante, advisor and secret lover sarah churchill, duchess of marlborough. sarah effectively rules the country through her influence on the queen until her impoverished cousin, abigail hill, arrives at court and undermines sarahâ€™s influence. this is a cross between â€˜all about eveâ€™ and â€˜orlandoâ€™ and is most appropriate in the #metoo era in that it is about three empowered women in a male dominated society where men are sidelined. this is about women and their desire, as both sarah and abigail battle for the queenâ€™s favour.
visually stunning both in design and cinematography. cameraman robbie ryan captures the action beautifully and low-light scenes are captivating and atmospheric which takes great skill.
alice fentonâ€™s set decoration and sandy powellâ€™s costume design are to be applauded with the contrast between abigailâ€™s feminine attire to sarahâ€™s more masculine, almost masochistic costumes. add to this the setting of principal photography being hatfield house in hertfordshire. 
the movieâ€™s main appeal is olivia colman, here donning regal robes in advance of her portrayal of queen elizabeth ii in â€˜the crownâ€™. colman is both regal and erratic throughout and what i love about her is her willingness to appear on screen warts and all.
so remarkable is that this drama is based on fact surrounding the three women in power and the extraordinary triangle they created.
a must-see for anyone wanting something apart from mainstream cinema. .
.
.
#oliviacolman #emmastone

text:
i guess iâ€™ll sink my teeth into this one. letâ€™s forget for a moment that gillette has a long history of misogynistic marketing and promotes a pink tax on their feminine products. letâ€™s instead invest the entirety of our focus on â€œtoxic masculinityâ€. what is toxic masculinity? to put it simply, it is described as the damage caused by the traditional expectations of manhood imposed on men. i guess i just donâ€™t understand the point of the video. itâ€™s conveying the message that men need to do better, as though our treatment of women has gotten worse in the past 70 years. my annoyance is not derived from the video itself, but by the praise itâ€™s garnered through its pointless narrative. 
while weâ€™re on the topic of â€œtoxic masculinityâ€, gillette, iâ€™d like to call the women of america to the stand. you are physically abusive toward men, knowing it is unlikely that you will have legal consequence. you manipulate divorces and child custody disputes in your favor. you commit filicide. you commit feticide. you too sexually harass unwilling coworkers in the workplace. you too cheat on your partners. you too bring down fellow women for personal gain. you too are a walking, breathing mistake that the earth coughed up. we all are. men and women alike are the scourge of this earth. so then, why are why targeting one another? why are we blaming the group when we should be blaming the individual? after all, you merely exercise your maliciousness in sneakier ways than the more overt tactics that are used by men.

my point it this: although i despise the term, toxic masculinity is a legitimate state of being in a mans mind. however, the issue i take on this subject is the ignorance with regards to itâ€™s feminine counterpart, toxic femininity. whereâ€™s that ad, gillette?

karachi-amidst the global #metoo storm, renowned actor and director angeline malik has decided to initiate a movement as an advocate to voicing relevant social issues in pakistan.

read more:Â zalmay khalilzad calls on coas gen qamar bajwa
inkaar karo will be the first of a series of movements that will creatively depict strong women coming together to stand against suppression. she has previously talked on subjects like child abuse and violence against women on a local and international level at appna and wapna conference in the us.

speaking about the campaign, angeline said: â€œthis initiative â€˜inkaar karo, hum tumhare saath hainâ€™ says a lot. i have heard many stories and seen a lot due to the nature of my work. itâ€™s hard to say no and it is even harder to speak up and make people believe you. i have brought together a group of strong women who feel the same as i do and we altogether want to convey the message that we hear you, we believe you and we will support you

text:
candid shot today. im a little better today. lack of sleep.. but that's my new normal...exhausted from all the headache of my house sustaining water damage from a recent storm.. construction hopefully starts soon. but for the moment i'm sitting in the dr. office, yet again. dealing with issues from my assault. 3fucking years later i'm still dealing with physical issues. most people don't realize that there are so many things survivors deal with, even years later. physical ones are what i get to add to my list of shit i'd rather not deal with, especially today/this week. i've noticed so many changes in my body, personality, psyche, habits, fears, insecurities.. the list goes on. all things that are because i was raped. i didn't realize that everything in my life had changed, even the slightest bit.. my life will never be the same. i do my best to keep track of the things that differ from before i was kidnapped so i can see what has changed and how i can best adapt. it is an ongoing task... sometimes overwhelming but nessasasry. i am grateful that i am alive to have the opportunity to see my kids grow.  life is about challenges and these are part of mine now. ...
...
...
...

text:
me too campaign is a tool to trap or breaking silence to win the war ? 
in my point of view on'me too'movement is it is surely a  tool which has broken many stereotypes running in our socielty since decades.it has shown the world that the most underrated and  considered a 'taboo' in our society is actually the most powerfull weapon we posses which is 'speaking up'.it has basically started a whirlwind revolution  all over the world of more aware and acknowledged society by giving every individual a voice to speaking up for ourselves. most of all it has given every individual a faith that their voices will be heard.it does have still plenty of loop holes and limitations but everything has a start,we still have a long way to go and i am thankful to the fact that the change has started.people aren't anymore dying in their misery and embarrassed about the wrong done to them instead they are getting out of their shells and speaking up against it.

yes,sadly this is the fact as per the current situation that #metoo movement has more to do with public figures than to reach out to common public facing such problems like sexual harassment in their day to day lives,but issues like sexual harassment has been part of our society since decades,there have been questions raised on it time and again,but before #metoo movement speaking up loud and lucid about such things was alien to our society say- 5years back.nobody spoke up about this ugly truth existing in our society since such a long time, even if someone did our society didn't  accept it as we should.people who spoke up were either made feel guilty themselves or were made subject to many  humiliations. 
so,i think that in a way the reason'me too' movement gained so much popularity because it is initiated by  public figures this has eventually played an influential role and for good i believe. 
i cherish the fact the change has started , i hope the day is not far our society will be impartial and justice serving. 
and let's not forget every idea starts from a thought and the thought has already been planted in our society through #metoo campaign,may it dwell well in coming future !! #campusprincess2019l

be kind to yourself. - cxx

true masculinity is expressed by respect for self and others, being powerful without having to display power, asserting oneself without victimizing others, expression without the need for unnecessary vulgarity, and exercising self control in uncomfortable situations. 
poise under pressure is the very essence of masculinity.

text:
waktu sma dulu, saya pernah mengurusi sesuatu di ruang guru. lupa ngurusin apa, yang jelas bukan ngurusin badan. pokoknya agak lama deh duduk di ruang guru.

pas lagi chilling gitu, tiba-tiba ada satu guru nyamperin saya. ibu-ibu. beliau mendekati saya dengan mata menyelidik, dan seketika bersabda, "ih kamu teh mirip artis yah"

saya tersipu. seumur-umur baru pertama kali dibilang mirip artis. teman-teman saya paling jauh bilang saya mirip hewan. bukan hewan buruk sih, hewannya eksotis gitu: tapir dan burung hantu. mirip artis? duhai, artis beruntung mana yang mukanya dimirip-miripkan dengan saya?
.
.
"iyaa, kamu teh mirip agus ringgo!"
.
.
maaf zac efron, maaf logan lerman, tapi artis yang mendapatkan kehormatan untuk mirip dengan saya adalah ringgo agus, seseorang yang pernah ikutan program katakan cinta di salah satu stasiun tv swasta.

senyum tersipu saya langsung luntur. sambil mencolek-colek saya, beliau bergumam asyik, "hihi, agus ringgo.." memang tidak separah yang dialami agni ketika dicolek hs di maluku sana, tapi saya jadi pengen ikutan #metoo gara-gara insiden ini. saya malu, bu...
.
.
sejak saat itu, saya selalu introspeksi di depan kaca. apa betul saya mirip dia? apa layak saya disamakan dengan dia?

10 tahun berlalu. ternyata ga buruk-buruk amat disama-samakan dengan dia. melihat riwayat pencapaiannya yang pernah menjadikan revalina s. temat sebagai mantan dan menjadikan sabai dieter sebagai pasangan hidup, ternyata mas ringgo sukses juga sebagai seorang artis meski setahu saya tidak pernah diasosiasikan dengan muka yang rupawan.

apalagi sejak ada bjorka. wah, saya yakin anak saya kelak bisa selucu bjorka, mayan bisa jadi passive income kalau ditaruh di instagram. daripada cuma jadi admin akun loker kan? heuheu

foto: keluarga sedap malam raya, bukan keluarga cemara.

#bukan10yearschallenge #apalagi30haribercerita

senyum tersipu saya langsung luntur. sambil mencolek-colek saya, beliau bergumam asyik, "hihi, agus ringgo.." memang tidak separah yang dialami agni ketika dicolek hs di maluku sana, tapi saya jadi pengen ikutan  gara-gara insiden ini. saya malu, bu...
.
.
sejak saat itu, saya selalu introspeksi di depan kaca. apa betul saya mirip dia? apa layak saya disamakan dengan dia?

10 tahun berlalu. ternyata ga buruk-buruk amat disama-samakan dengan dia. melihat riwayat pencapaiannya yang pernah menjadikan revalina s. temat sebagai mantan dan menjadikan sabai dieter sebagai pasangan hidup, ternyata mas ringgo sukses juga sebagai seorang ais meski setahu saya tidak pernah diasosiasikan dengan muka yang rupawan.

apalagi sejak ada bjorka. wah, saya yakin anak saya kelak bisa selucu bjorka, mayan bisa jadi passive income kalau ditaruh di instagram. daripada cuma jadi admin akun loker kan? heuheu

text:
daughters of then..... as the planets align, 
know this is bigger than you. 
in the chaos of days, find the familiar
in the sights, sounds, smells, touch, tastes & feels

connect to the rhythm of something other than the bluelight, 
maybe the sun, moon, the tide, the river or forest, the desert or sky. 
feel the saltwater effect, 
the sweat, the sea and tears, bringing calm, releasing doubt and fears. 
at the space between a new and full moon eclipse, i find myself, in 1979, standing on a shagpile carpet, in our loungeroom at lake albert in wagga, nsw; wearing my favourite red terry towelling short jumpsuit, starring into the new colour tv. 
mesmerized, by the haunting predictions of coastal flooding, as graphically shared in a nostadamus special, aired after mike willisee's a current affair, shown before cop shop and the don lane show. 
i couldn't tell you the other predictions that day, but 40 years on, i remember it as if it was yesterday. 
the symbolism and stoic grace of this moment in time, was to unexpectedly weave it's way, through my life cycle, like the changing tides. 
1. appearing in 2001 at the maroochy rsl club, with us author sherrill sellman, in her book hormone heresy. in it nostadamus is quoted....... "there will be an unprecedented time in history, when the influence of the feminine will transform all society, unlike anything in the last 5000 years, where there will be a massive experience of renewal and a new vision of harmony" 
2. 2006 in the trauma of unspoken first trimester miscarriage, nostadamus again aired on a special in a hotel room in gosford, nsw

3. 2010 painting a patterned mandela, inspired by napolean hill's book, think and grow rich, in which he recommends nightly counsel with a round table of associates, chosen from any place in time. 
in my painting, nostadamus sits in the 3pm position, between joan of arc and galileo....interestingly, all vindicated by the patriarchy. 
although, perhaps, like the tales of nostadamous, fairy tales too are sewn into our dna, intrinsically woven in a way to keep us safe, from something. .....continued in comments ğŸ’—
name: Karen Mahoney
tweet_full:
daughters of then..... as the planets align, 
know this is bigger than you. 
in the chaos of days, find the familiar
in the sights, sounds, smells, touch, tastes & feels

connect to the rhythm of something other than the bluelight, 
maybe the sun, moon, the tide, the river or forest, the desert or sky. 
feel the saltwater effect, 
the sweat, the sea and tears, bringing calm, releasing doubt and fears. 
at the space between a new and full moon eclipse, i find myself, in 1979, standing on a shagpile carpet, in our loungeroom at lake albert in wagga, nsw; wearing my favourite red terry towelling short jumpsuit, starring into the new colour tv. 
mesmerized, by the haunting predictions of coastal flooding, as graphically shared in a nostadamus special, aired after mike willisee's a current affair, shown before cop shop and the don lane show. 
i couldn't tell you the other predictions that day, but 40 years on, i remember it as if it was yesterday. 
the symbolism and stoic grace of this moment in time, was to unexpectedly weave it is way, through my life cycle, like the changing tides. 
1. appearing in 2001 at the maroochy rsl club, with us author sherrill sellman, in her book hormone heresy. in it nostadamus is quoted....... "there will be an unprecedented time in history, when the influence of the feminine will transform all society, unlike anything in the last 5000 years, where there will be a massive experience of renewal and a new vision of harmony" 
2. 2006 in the trauma of unspoken first trimester miscarriage, nostadamus again aired on a special in a hotel room in gosford, nsw

3. 2010 painting a patterned mandela, inspired by napolean hill's book, think and grow rich, in which he recommends nightly counsel with a round table of associates, chosen from any place in time.

although, perhaps, like the tales of nostadamous, fairy tales too are sewn into our dna, intrinsically woven in a way to keep us safe, from something. .....continued in comments ğŸ’—

most days i ignore but im always reminded that with great privilege comes great responsibility . 
the world is changed by our willingness to take a stand.  to say #nomore 
i stand for #truth and #integrity and a willingness to stand up even when iâ€™m the only one. 
because i know what it feels like to realize how many â€œgood peopleâ€ knew... how many knew and did nothing because it wasnâ€™t their problem or it wasnâ€™t impacting them directly. 
i wonâ€™t be the person who sits down when cruelty or injustice happens. 
the only thing for me is now i donâ€™t carry it.  i know how to process and let go and move on. 
but itâ€™s my humble opinion that the more of us that stand up when we see something thatâ€™s not ok - the better. 
thatâ€™s where courage lives.  to get in the ring, anyway.  to stand up anyway.  to use your voice, anyway. 
itâ€™s not about winning, itâ€™s about being a part of the solution... no matter how many times we have to speak up or stand up. 
keep standing up. 
keep showing up. 
keep going.

text:
gillette released an advert the other day (if you havenâ€™t seen it go and watch it) which marked a new branding strategy for their organisation. it was dope! it touches on toxic masculinity and includes snippets from the coverage of the #metoo movement over the last couple of years. there are a lot of really strong and really positive messages in the advert about what we expect from men and boys and the harm that these expectations and stereotypes can perpetuate. â£
â €â €â£
i donâ€™t have much to say about the advert, i really like it, but what i will say is this is not it. gillette havenâ€™t fixed the problem and the campaign doesnâ€™t right the decades of wrongs that p&g have committed. itâ€™s a start, and a very strong one, but letâ€™s try not to get caught up in these grand gestures. â£
â €â €â£
the real work has been and is being done, day in and day out by women and men who were facilitating these conversations before it was cool to do so. shouts goes out to all the peeps out here really grinding to change the world. â£
â €â €â£

text:
can we just take a moment out and appreciate #metoo campaign for the support and courage it has provided to the people worldwide.
talking about the harassment that one has gone through isnâ€™t easy, it is challenging to put certain obnoxious acts into words for the society and what is more challenging is preparing yourself for  criticism for being honest. knowing that people will come out and ask for proofs and question the authenticity of the allegations. the purpose of #meetoo movement is to empower people through empathy, especially young men and women who are vulnerable.
in a country like india it takes decades to seek justice so if not justice at least after being exposed in the society such sort of inhuman race will know that certain acts canâ€™t be hidden for long.
the more people are hesitant the more these wicked faces hide behind the rock and will continue doing such awful deeds.
they need to be exposed in the society and that is what #metoo did and will continue doing.
not taking a stand against such harassments and assaults is equivalent to standing with assaulter . today no workplace is safe, people go through sexual assaults everyday so even if thereâ€™s one person standing against it, makes a difference and it is us who needs to create a difference. there will be people around us who are willing not to believe but thatâ€™s okay, this is how our society is but we are also going to find people who are willing to listen, believe and change the world.
this is what #metoo is all about. it is about those people who want to be heard by the society and about those who want to listen and are willing to create a change.
those who act ignorant to such harassments are the ones who will continue being the same for the rest of their lives, not wanting to change the world for good.
so only if we want see a change in our workplace and want to feel safe we need to act upon it. 
#campusprincess2019

text:
day 11/21 of things i'm thankful for:

1. this commercial that gave me goosebumps and made me cry. i'm thankful that a company is risking the loss of profits to make a stand and change the landscape of what we see in the media. as a #metoo survivor of rape, i applaud companies that aren't perpetuating the subconscious/unconscious messages of power that men can get. "boys will be boys" is not an okay excuse to allow boys/men to bully, intimidate, be physically aggressive with one another, or to disrespect or objectify women. @gillette just got a new customer--i will now be making a point to buy gillette razors for our household! 
2. the message i heard during yoga today with my amazing yoga instructor, @mysticmoon_chiara . the message was focused on the full lunar eclipse coming this sunday and how now is the time to have the courage to be authentically you. (<--this seems to be a theme that keeps showing up in my life. i guess i'm on the right track). she shared a quote from ernest hemingway--"courage is grace under pressure." she went on to talk about how that grace, that humility, allows us to move forward into the truth of who we are. that it's important not to power through it and force the forward motion but to move forward gently and mindfully. that sometimes we will be moving forward and sometimes we will need to retract to be gentle with ourselves. she also mentioned that dogs are put in our lives to teach us how to love others unconditionally and cats are put in our lives to teach us how to love ourselves. because that's what cats do. they take care of themselves first and foremost. now, i'm totally allergic to cats so i won't be adding a cat to my life but the idea of the way that cats are fully authentic with who they are and what they choose to do will be something i plan to be more mindful of incorporating into my life. 
3. that i'm in a place in my life where i'm open to change, growth, and  forward motion. i used to blame my shortcomings on my parents and on my circumstances. after lots of hard work, (continued ğŸ‘‡ğŸ½)

#didyouknow #learning about
autism spectrum disorder. it is a serious developmental disorder that impairs the ability to communicate and interact.

common
#facts
- more thanÂ 100 thousandÂ cases per year (nigeria)
- treatment can help, but this condition can't be cured
- chronic: can last for years or be lifelong
- requires a medical diagnosis
- lab tests or imaging rarely required
advice - consult a doctor for medical advice

text:
#tbt to the time @thirdeyeblind posted a pic of my sister and i at last years womanâ€™s march. 
back story: a few months earlier i had tearfully revealed to my family that i had been the victim of sexual assault. the assault happened many years earlier and i had kept it from my family for more reasons than i can begin to talk about. we marched together as a family in support of anyone else who has been a victim/survivor of any attack beyond their control, be it physical, mental, racial, religious, political or otherwise. the words on my sign are lyrics from a third eye blind song called â€œwoundedâ€ that tells the story of a survivor and the narrators wish that she could return to her life as it was before she was hurt. the other side of my sign read â€œshow up woundedâ€ another lyric from this song that has meant so much to me over the years. no matter what happens in life, no matter what demons youâ€™re battling itâ€™s so important that you remember to just show up! keep moving, keep breathing, keep fighting and keep healing. you are not alone #metoo #survivor #womansmarch #strongertogether #thirdeyeblind #nyc #speakup #speakout #heal #yourenotalone #resist #bebetterhumans

#
indian bollywood producer and director rajkumar hirani at the mumbai film festival in 2015. (str/afp/getty images) digital producer and writer january 17 at 1:35 pm it was too good to be true. that was the reaction of so many of us indian women as we watched the nationâ€™s #metoo movement getting traction last year â€” and apparently, we were right. for all of the progress made in the past few months in discussing sexual harassment, the underlying culture that blames survivors and protects abusive men remains intact. this week, famed director rajkumar hirani â€” who directed â€œ3 idiots,â€ one of the most successful hindi films of all time â€” was accused of sexual assault by a woman who worked with him on his latest film. the accuser, who has remained anonymous, says that hirani sexually abused her on multiple occasions between march and september 2018, according to huffington post india. vinod chopra films, which produced the movie, has set up an investigative committee and vowed to look into the complaint. (hirani has denied the allegations, calling them â€œfalse, malicious and mischievous.â€) hirani is just the latest name in a long list of bollywood celebrities accused of harassment or assault. indiaâ€™sâ€¦

text:
i absolutely adore this #strongwoman. 
artemisia gentileschi was born in rome in the time that #caravaggio was king artist of italy.
her father taught her how to paint, but what he couldnâ€™t instruct he hired his friends to teach. her perspective teacher took advantage of her youth and beauty. he raped her repeatedly with the promise of marriage allowed him to do as he wished. yet, he was already married.
upon finding out, her father took him to court. artemisia was subjected to courtroom gynecological exams and the thumb screws. her rapist was eventually found guilty and never served time. 
her name was tainted. to avoid ruin, her father married her off to a young florentine. she was happy for a while. her artwork gained in popularity. she rubbed elbows with #galileo and created artworks for the #medicis.
florence also brought sadness. infertility, child mortality, debt, marital strife, and gossip. she left with her sole surviving child, a girl named after her mother who died when artemisia was a small girl, #prudencia. 
she then traveled to venice, then to naples to make her own path, her own way, her own work. she supported herself and her daughter.
therefore, as she said, â€œmy illustrious lordship, iâ€™ll show you what a woman can do.â€
her artwork reflects #strongwomen and the peril of tainted reputations. her stories are powerful and offer an insider view from the eyes of a gender that was seen as lesser.
she is a true strong woman and inspiration.
#artemisiagentileschi #baroque #metoo #awomansworth #shepersisted #strongwomen #artistmom

text:
our new website, www.batteredmotherscustodyconference.org, is live!  visit us and register for the fabulous upcoming 14th bmcc to be held april 26th-28th, 2019 at the beautiful desmond hotel in albany. get your hotel rooms at the early bird rate of $108.  spread the word, protective moms, dv advocates, and allies!  the battered mothers custody conference (#bmcc is an annual weekend event dedicated to educating professionals and the general public about the serious legal and psychological challenges faced by battered women who seek protection for themselves and their children from the family/divorce court system. these (primarily) survivors of domestic violence often encounter disbelief of their allegations of intimate partner and/or child abuse by the legal agents involved in their child custody cases.
â€‹
the conference aims to inform, support, and advocate for these survivors, allowing them to network with each other and with the professionals and advocates who come to present at the conference. the conference aims to help survivors enhance their ability to better cope with and overcome the impacts of abuse and to better advocate for themselves and their children within the legal arena.
â€‹
each conference is designed around a theme around with most if not all of the sessions and workshops revolve. the next battered mothers custody conference, "combining protective mothers movement with the #metoo movement," will take place on april 26th, 27th, and 28th, 2019 at the desmond hotel in albany, new york #batteredwomen #batteredmother #batteredwoman #domesticviolence #domesticviolencesurvivor #domesticviolenceawareness

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

meet dr. latoya lee, bfsâ€™s resident physician for the show. she received  a degree in biology from spelman college before going on to earn her medical degree from meharry medical college. she believes that a strong doctor-patient relationship and preventative care are the key to improving healthcare. in her spare time, dr. lee enjoys spending time with her family, volunteering, and watching or playing sports. her favorite place to visit is her her familyâ€™s farm in georgia because it reminds her of her history and the sacrifices that were made so she could achieve her dream of becoming a physician. text:
ğŸŒŸ meet #ywrnewyork speaker amanda septimo. get your conference tickets today (link in bio). ğŸŒŸ 
born and raised in the south bronx, amanda septimo has a long, rich history of service to the community that began with community activism in her teens. over the years amanda has worked with local community organizations to advance an agenda of inclusive, sustainable, and responsible growth in the bronx. 
most recently, amanda septimo ran for new york state assembly in the bronxâ€™s 84th district. the core message of her campaign was built on the ideas that everyone deserves access to opportunity, and that we must support policies that work to uplift the entire community.

prior to running for state assembly, amanda septimo worked with the council of school supervisors and administrators (csa) to ensure that school leaders and students have the resources they need to transform every school into a thriving learning environment. 
before joining csa, amanda septimo spent four years working with congressman jose e. serrano in the bronx. in 2014, amanda became one of the youngest serving senior staffers in congress when she was promoted to district director for the 15th congressional district. in her time as district director, amanda septimo significantly expanded the pool of federal resources in the district and amplified the array of services available to constituents. @amandaseptimo .

text:
movie review â€“ soni
the movie starts off with a shot of one guy whistling at a girl while both are cycling which leads to eve teasing and the guy is severely beaten up by the girl who we later discover is a police officer(soni).
the movie is about two young female police (soni and kalpana) officers who are on a mission to catch all the men who commit any crime of violence against women (however their mission is unclear to me till the second half of the movie).
while soni is a badass cop who will not let any guy get away with misbehavior towards women and is always angry because of her professional and personal life, kalpana is soni's superior who wants to follow the law and stay within it. while both of them are this authoritative at work (and great at their job), they are completely opposite outside work and this variation of both the characters was a joy to watch.
the movie is based in or around delhi and i must say the casting of this movie is phenomenal. it felt so real and the credit goes to the director who could bring out the best from all the actors.
halfway through the movie i felt that it could either be a preachy bollywood movie or keep it real and show how it is and i am glad that they decided not to go the bollywood preachy way. the movie was raw, real and unnerving at times.
this movie made me think about the problems going on in india with the indian police system (who wants to just do moral poilicing and take money instead of doing the right thing) and the fact that every hour probably some girl is getting teased by a guy somewhere in the country. why canâ€™t we understand that this is not right? when a girl says no it means no. we need to get to the root of this problem and start from scratch. the boys need to be taught to respect women and the men who do wrong need to be set right. with the #metoo movement becoming so big in india there should be a committee in all professions who will not only look into this problem but also get rid of it from itâ€™s root.
i had great expectations from the movie and it lived up to itâ€™s potential. the movie is fast paced and will definitely keep you hooked. a much recommended movie.
rating â€“ 4/5

text:
if someone tells me they've been abused, or dealt with racism, sexism or transphobia. anything that compromises their safety and well being i'm going to believe them.
believing them does not "hurt" the person they are talking about. it presses them for accountability the only thing getting "hurt" there is their ego and possible false public persona.
we all need healing, including abusers but that won't happen with denial of the truth and hiding in pain.
some of the people who do these acts are activists, parents, spiritual leaders and community healers. it is absolutely frustrating and painful to watch your abuser be upheld and celebrated while you cradle their status in direct violence to your well being. - no one should be shamed for their silence about their abuse, its our personal journey. but there should be a choice to come forward if you need to and not the worry that you'll be shamed and discarded! i really encourage people who have been abusive to start holding themselves accountable.

thankful for you @kushridevi @kay_sonilal @zanchal .
.

text_retweet:
i'll be completely honest. i've been waiting years for marc emery to finally get put on blast and it looks like he's finally getting his #metoo moment. when i was first entering the world of cannabis activism i had a friend warn me about mr. emery and his alleged activities... i'm glad i decided to heed that warning.

i'm so grateful to journalist deidre olsen for coming out with their own story and also for providing a platform for emery's other alleged victims to tell their stories. link to their full twitter thread is here: https://goo.gl/zonsa5 ... i just posted a few choice entries.

unfortunately, the prohibition and stigma around cannabis has provided a smokescreen for predators for too long. "nobody cares, nobody will believe you, because you do drugs." ... no longer can we allow this to happen in our proud cannabis community. #believesurvivors #ibelieveyou 
as a sex and body positive cannabis educator, i find mr. emery's take on anal sex coercive and disturbing, not to mention misogynistic and heterocissexist (let's not forget his past tweets regarding the trans community). i'd like to remind everyone that while some jitters are to be expected when trying something new, it is not okay to assume that your cock is a magic remedy for your partner's fears and doubts. 100% consent, 100% of the time. the end.

as demonstrated by the last picture in the slides, marc emery has been permitted to get away with predatory comments and behaviour for far too long. this is not okay and we must work toward deplatforming him at the very least. 
it's time to take out the trash. ğŸš® #deplatforming #believewomen #cannabisculture #marcemery #humangarbage #canada420 #canadianstoners #cloudsovercanada #stonernation420 #cannabiscommunity

edit: in the original text of this post i used the wrong pronouns for mx. olsen who goes by they/them. if you've reposted this gram, please edit accordingly. thank you.

text:
just watched a video by @kristinakuzmic titled #outthem and it got me all stirred up. you really have to watch it, but in it she tells everyone about the men who troll her pages posting sexually explicit comments.
___________________________________________
apparently one man repeatedly posted this type of comment to her publicly in the comment section of her posts. so she put him on blast here on instagram. then something insane happened. a few of her followers chastised her for outing him. this is why she released her new video, encouraging women to #outthem. because why should we be expected to cover up their wrongdoings? why should we have to live in silence while we are being sexually harassed?
___________________________________________
this video hit me hard today because just in the past week i have had creeps slide into my dms with disgusting, unwanted sexual comments. comments like â€œso you like posting pictures naked?â€ ... and a reply to one of my pregnancy photos â€œi need to hit that.â€ ğŸ¤®
___________________________________________
seriously, it makes my stomach lurch to get comments like that from strangers. it makes my skin crawl. it infringes upon my right to express myself and post my art or the art of others without being sexually harassed. 
___________________________________________
hey men: it is not okay to force yourselves onto women. it is not okay to randomly post sexual comments/send sexual messages to strangers on the internet ever. stop being a fucking creep and get off my page. iâ€™m not here for you, iâ€™m not posting to lure you here, and i would appreciate it if you would refrain from talking to me. 
___________________________________________

___________________________________________

besonders berÃ¼hrt hat mich und auch die teilnehmerinnen der vortrag von sandra norak. sie berichtete nicht nur offen von ihren eigenen erfahrungen in der prostituion, sondern ordnete sie auch kritisch ein in den politischen und menschenrechtlichen kontext: prostitution ist gewalt an frauen und eine menschenrechtsverletzung. 
von der franzÃ¶sischen senatorin und ehemaligen frauenrechtsministerin laurence rossignol erhielten wir aktuelle, interessante und wichtige informationen aus erster hand zum franzÃ¶sischen erfolg des "nordischen models". frankreich hatte 2016 die freierbestrafung, also das sexkauf-verbot eingefÃ¼hrt, das mittlerweile in der gesellschaft auf breite akzeptanz trifft - vor allem wegen der #metoo skandale, die der bewusstseins bildung noch einmal schub verliehen haben. 
in der deutschen politik stehen die mdb leni breymaier (spd) und frank heinrich (cdu) fÃ¼r die einfÃ¼hrung des nordischen modells. sie haben zu dem parlamentarischen abend geladen. 
nach den vortrÃ¤gen diskutierte das interessierte und kompetente publikum, darunter vertreterinnen aller parteien und expertinnen, ob und wie das nordische modell in deutschland umgesetzt werden kann und welche â€flankierenden maÃŸnahmenâ€œ seitens der politik sinnvoll wÃ¤ren - im falle einer erfolgreichen einfÃ¼hrung der freierbestrafung bei uns. 
wir von terre des femmes e.v. und solwodi deutschland e.v. fordern zusammen mit unseren mitstreitern das nordische modell - also auch das sexkaufverbot - und damit einen gesellschaftlichen perspektivwechsel. hin zu einer gesellschaft ohne prostitution.

text:
this is happening on mlk day at the african american museum in dallas. #mlk #conversations #communityleaders 
join local community leaders for a candid panel discussion, â€œ#metoo: weâ€™re still talking about it,â€ at realizing the dream healthy living expo at 3:00 pm on monday, january 21, 2019, at the african american museum in dallas. each week, there are new reports of sexual abuse in the arts and entertainment industry, sexual harassment in the workplace, and the prevalence of rape culture on college campuses. 
panelists will examine how widespread and systemic these issues are, explore the roles of women and men in dismantling sexual violence and discuss how these unresolved issues continue to affect the health of the community. the discussion will be moderated by community and business leader rev. carl m. lavallais, president of nâ€™credible consulting. 
the event is free. you are encouraged to attend this discussion and share what are you going to do about the systemic issue of sexual harassment. 
hear from:

denise lee, award-winning actress and singer, and founder of community conversation, a monthly gathering of open dialogue geared toward healing the racial tension in our communities; featured in the upcoming documentary, shatter the silence (wow films)

gwendolyn jones, founder and president of arise! international, an organization that provides support to survivors of sexual trauma

rev. jonathan grace, pastor of church at the square, a ministry serving the homeless citizens of dallas

vincent l. hall, columnist with texas metro news and garland journal and community activist

and i'll be there! 3pm this monday (mlk day) at the african american museum in fair park, dallas.

#africanamericanmuseumdallas #fairpark

i knew him. 
he was actually one of my friends, before everything went to hell. 
he was a few years older than me, and there was this family party that we were at. i had a really good book that i wanted to read, so i escaped to a secluded corner. he was clearly intoxicated when he found me. he said my name, and snuggled next to me. politely, i moved away, and kept reading, showing that i had absolutely no interest in whatever was happening. he put his hand on my thigh, and whined. â€œcome on, pay attention.â€ he whined and whined, until i finally looked at him. 
he started massaging my thighs, and i moved away. he kept whining for me to pay attention, and i kept moving away and away until i was backed against the wall and he reached up my shirt and for my bra. his friend found him and dragged him away, apologizing, and i had been so terrified, i felt faint and i thought i was going to suffocate. i donâ€™t know what wouldâ€™ve happened if his friend hadnâ€™t showed up. -anonymous.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this year, 2019, is my 10 year anniversary of me reporting first to my parents (at age 27) that i am a child sexual abuse survivor, starting at age 5 for numerous years. it took me 22 years to be able to report. 
i donâ€™t want pitty, or any poor yous. i donâ€™t want to be treated any differently. 
i have always been a strong beautifully fearless woman who can and will do all things i have always dreamed. 
what i do want is to give anyone who needs help reporting, my strength. and encourage them to speak up and share their story. it will probably be the hardest words they will ever speak. but it will bring light to the darkness. 
if you are lucky enough to not be personally affected by abuse, i urge you to be there for someone you has. advocate. march. vote. protest. speak up. be an ally. 
if you are struggling with sharing your story because of the shame or thinking itâ€™s your fault, please, reach out to someone you trust. get help. 
not everyone will understand but the right people will be there and you will heal and one day you will finally believe it was not your fault. 
so if anyone is struggling, #believeme it gets better. the strength and empowerment i have today, i never believed was possible. spread love. 
with the current political and social climate it is more important than ever for us to #fightback together and say #enough is enough. 
#believesurivivors #10yearchallenge #metoo #timesup #allies #traumasurvivor

text:
laura lefkow-hynes had long viewed her teenage relationship with her chemistry teacher at lincoln park high school as mutual, though dysfunctional. then, as an adult with a daughter of her own and the #metoo movement, she began to see it differently. â €
â €
â€œabuse doesnâ€™t always look like a sexual relationship of some kind. it can be emotional, and it can be destructive,â€ said lefkow-hynes, 34, who is a lawyer. â€œand it can happen to anyone.â€ â €
â €
she wrote a letter to chicago public schools officials in october 2017 to make them aware that one of their current employees had been in an inappropriate relationship with her during her sophomore and junior years. sharing journal entries, she described to cps investigators what she recalled: the pet names, the long late-night phone calls, him holding her hand and brushing his mouth against her neck. driving her in his car. chastising her when she kissed a boy at a party. â €
â €
after interviews and email reviews, cps determined lefkow-hynesâ€™ account was credible. the district removed james galinski from school grounds earlier this year. click the link in our bio for the full story. (jose m. osorio / chicago tribune | @joseochicagotrib)

text:
spiritual message for january 2-february 6, 2019
#thestar #fiveofswords #sixofwands #eightofwands #james117 #crownchakra #impartiality 
this month and year is starting out on a strong foot forward with #newmoonincapricorn on january 5, uranus going direct at the same time, all planets out of retrograde until march 5th and the #lunareclipse #fullmooninleo #leofullmoon on january 22. eclipses are cosmic events that spur us into action, sometimes by orchestrating dramatic and/or unexpected events. it is definitely a time of things getting the spotlight, especially issues that've been long over due for us to pay attention to as a society and finally do something about it. what's done in the dark, will get exposed. for example, look at the numerous incidents of #metoo incidents in the news, or the #survivingrkelly #muterkelly docuseries released on january 6. this is a year of getting back into balance between the spiritual and the physical. as a society, we are out of balance spiritually, which in turn affects us on a physical level. we are shifting from the divide and conquer mentality towards a more humanitarian and fair one as represented by the star card. right now, we are so divided by our selfish, tribalistic ego drives and it is so easy for us to be this way with social media being used to promote fear and anxiety propaganda. we as a society will be forced to deal with our leadership and the character and values of those in leadership and influential positions as shown in the 6 of wands, whether they are in our governments, celebrities, or social issues such as #patriarchy #toxicmasculinity etc. 2019 is the year of accountability and fairness. we will be looking for leadership that instills optimism, inspiration, and confidence within society especially as #election2020 draws near. it is time for us to work for the greater good, for ourselves and one another along the lines of universal love, humanitarianism, collectivism. it is a time to start following our dreams and be inspired and be hopeful for the future, even when things may look otherwise. hope this message inspire and empowers all who read this. have an awesome 2019!
#foodforthought #mindbodyspirit
